ducators, and nurses to their families and community. Yet as Jane E. Dabel demonstrates, separate spheres were not a reality for New York City's black people, who faced dire poverty, a lopsided sex ratio, racialized violence, and a high mortality rate, all of which conspired to prevent men from gaining respectable employment and political clout. Consequently, many black women came out of the home and into the streets to work, build networks with other women, and fight against racial injustice. A Respectable Woman reveals the varied and powerful lives led by black women, who, despite the exhortations of male reformers, occupied public roles as gender and race reformers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aAfrican American womenxHistoryx19th centuryxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aAfrican American womenxPolitical activityxHistoryx19th centuryxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aAfrican American womenxPolitical activityzNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy19th century. 0aAfrican American womenxSocial conditionsx19th centuryxNew York (State)xNew YorkxNew York (State)xNew YorkxHistory. 0aAfrican American womenzNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy19th century. 0aAfrican American womenzNew York (State)zNew YorkxSocial conditionsy19th century. 0aCommunity lifexHistoryx19th centuryxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aCommunity lifezNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy19th century. 0aRacismxHistoryx19th centuryxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aRacismzNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy19th century. 0aSex rolexHistoryx19th centuryxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aSex rolezNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy19th century. 0aWomen's rightsxHistoryx19th centuryxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aWomen's rightszNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy19th century. 4aTells. 4abeing. 4ablack. 